%N A388054 Numbers k > 2 such that (k - 2^m)*2^m + 1 is prime for every m > 0 with 2^m < k.
%C A388054 Are there only finitely many such numbers?
%C A388054 Question: does every such odd number have to be a prime?
%C A388054 If so, then (k - 2^m)*2^m + 1 is also prime (equal to k) for m = 0.
%C A388054 No more (neither even nor odd) terms k < 10^8. - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 14 2025
%t A388054 q[k_] := AllTrue[Range[1, Ceiling[Log2[k]]-1], PrimeQ[(k - 2^#)*2^# + 1] &]; Select[Range[3, 250], q] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 14 2025 *)
%o A388054 (PARI) isok(k) = if (k>2, my(m=1); while(2^m < k, if (!ispseudoprime((k - 2^m)*2^m + 1), return(0)); m++); return(1);); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Sep 14 2025
